I also agree with this definition. I am skeptical. There is nothing  
to be ashamed of there. Being skeptical led me to the conclusion that  
there is some genuine paranormal phenomenon. It doesn&#39;t need to be a  
case of all or nothing. Some genuine events is good enough. All it  
takes is one white crow to prove there are white crows, not that all  
crows are white or need to be.

Ann
I think I&#39;m losing my cutting edge this evening already....



On Jan 18, 2008, at 8:29 PM, Guy wrote:

&gt; Oh - and I tend to agree with this explanation from &quot;Skeptic&quot;
&gt; magazine:
&gt;
&gt; &quot;...Some people believe that skepticism is the rejection of new
&gt; ideas, or worse, they confuse &quot;skeptic&quot; with &quot;cynic&quot; and think that
&gt; skeptics are a bunch of grumpy curmudgeons unwilling to accept any
&gt; claim that challenges the status quo. This is wrong. Skepticism is a
&gt; provisional approach to claims. It is the application of reason to
&gt; any and all ideas — no sacred cows allowed. In other words,
&gt; skepticism is a method, not a position. Ideally, skeptics do not go
&gt; into an investigation closed to the possibility that a phenomenon
&gt; might be real or that a claim might be true. When we say we
&gt; are &quot;skeptical,&quot; we mean that we must see compelling evidence before
&gt; we believe...&quot;
&gt;
&gt; (http://www.skeptic.com/about_us/discover_skepticism.html)
&gt;
&gt; In this regard - I consider myself a skeptic...one who practices/uses
&gt; skepticism. Note that this concept cuts both ways. For example - some
&gt; EVP is explained away as &quot;apophenia&quot;. When you really dig into that
&gt; term - you find that it is used inappropriately.
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;ve started calling people like James Randi, etc. &quot;discreditors&quot;.
&gt; Not only do they NOT believe in various abilities/stories/etc. (at
&gt; least publicly) but they ACTIVELY ridicule the people and their work
&gt; whom they disagree with and attempt to rally others to this cause.
&gt;
&gt; Guy
